body:
Given the following code: https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2021&gist=64b6016c52540326f735849e3014159a

```rust
use std::collections::HashMap;
pub fn main() {
    let mut map: HashMap<&'static str, Test> = HashMap::new();
    map.insert("a", Test::A);
    let value = map.get("a");
    let value_unwrapped = value.unwrap();
    let test: Test = value_unwrapped.clone();
}

enum Test {
    A,
    B,
}
```

The current output is:

```
error[E0308]: mismatched types
 --> src/main.rs:7:22
  |
7 |     let test: Test = value_unwrapped.clone();
  |               ----   ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ expected enum `Test`, found `&Test`
  |               |
  |               expected due to this

For more information about this error, try `rustc --explain E0308`.
error: could not compile `playground` due to previous error
```

<!--
If the problem is not self-explanatory, please provide a rationale for the
change.
-->
This error output is confusing and obscures the real error, which is the lack of Clone implementation on the Test enum. 
The output could possibly be something like this:
```
  |
4 |     let cloned = a.clone();
  |                    ^^^^^ method not found in `Test`
...
7 | enum Test {
  | --------- method `clone` not found for this
  |
  = help: items from traits can only be used if the trait is implemented and in scope
  = note: the following trait defines an item `clone`, perhaps you need to implement it:
          candidate #1: `Clone`
```

which is the error output of this code: https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2021&gist=58bdcf9b2de0cd0c7d75f00a0bd1a7e3

```rust
pub fn main() {
    let a = Test::A;
    let cloned = a.clone();
}

enum Test {
    A,
    B,
}
```
